  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Ye call me Master and Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Master in the sense of Teacher. The word in the original is not “Rabbi.” (Comp. Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 11:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The Jewish pupils called their teachers “Rabbi” and “Mar” (Teacher), and it was not permitted to any pupil to call his teacher by his proper name (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sanhedr.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " fol. 100, §1). The word “Master” here refers to His position as their Teacher; the word Lord to the reverence which they paid to Him. These were the common titles of everyday life which He here asserts for Himself.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
